-- Article 1: The State of the Modern Travel Marketplace
UPDATE public.newsroom_articles
SET
  author_id = 'd4ec9c8f-0b9f-4e6e-ad2f-f8c701df028e',
  subtitle = 'Why infinite choice has made the modern traveler more anxious — and what comes after the algorithm.',
  excerpt = 'The modern traveler has more information than ever, and less confidence in what to book. A founder''s field report on the quiet collapse of algorithmic travel.',
  hero_image_url = 'https://iwdevxltjuedijrcdejs.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/newsroom-media/articles/hero-state-of-marketplace.jpg',
  hero_image_alt = 'A traveler in a luxury airport lounge at dusk, overlooking the airfield.',
  hero_image_credit = 'Photograph for Goldsainte',
  og_image_url = 'https://iwdevxltjuedijrcdejs.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/newsroom-media/articles/hero-state-of-marketplace.jpg',
  tags = ARRAY['Travel Industry','Modern Luxury','Marketplaces','Discovery'],
  body = E'A few years ago, I sat in a hotel lounge in Lisbon and watched the woman next to me plan her trip on six tabs at once.\n\nKayak. Skyscanner. TripAdvisor. Reddit. Booking.com. A creator''s Notion template she had paid eleven dollars for.\n\nShe was visibly exhausted.\n\nShe had access to more travel information than any generation in history — and less confidence in what to book.\n\nThat moment didn''t feel like an outlier. It felt like the industry.\n\n> Travel became optimized for search engines instead of people.\n\n## The quiet collapse of algorithmic travel\n\nFor twenty years, the promise was that more options would equal better trips.\n\nIt did not.\n\nIt equaled more browser tabs. More recommendation engines pulling in opposite directions. Hotel "deals" priced by surge algorithms that change between a coffee and the second sip. Reviews written by people whose definition of luxury was a continental breakfast.\n\nWe got volume. We lost taste.\n\nThe affluent traveler — the one who used to call a trusted advisor in midtown Manhattan and have a Tuscan itinerary in her inbox by Friday — quietly stopped trusting the internet to plan her week off.\n\n![A linen-draped table at sunset on the Amalfi coast with a glass of wine, a bowl of lemons, and a leather travel journal.](https://iwdevxltjuedijrcdejs.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/newsroom-media/articles/inline-mediterranean.jpg)\n\n## Recommendations aren''t taste\n\nMost travel recommendations today are written for Google rankings, not human beings.\n\nThat sentence is uncomfortable because it''s obvious.\n\nThe top result for "where to eat in Rome" is not where Romans eat. It''s where someone with good SEO eats. There is a difference, and travelers — especially well-traveled ones — can feel it the moment they sit down.\n\nThe best trips are rarely discovered through filters.\n\nThey come from a sentence:\n\n> "Skip the Eiffel Tower at sunset. Go to the rooftop of Printemps an hour before close. Bring a coat."\n\nThat is taste. Algorithms can''t fake it. They can only collect data about it after the fact.\n\n## What the modern traveler actually wants\n\nIn private conversations with travelers across our marketplace, the same themes return:\n\n- They want a person, not a portal.\n- They want a perspective, not 412 options.\n- They want someone to take the bad ideas off the table.\n- They want their time back.\n- They want to feel something — anticipation, intimacy, a sense that someone designed this for them.\n\nThe under-served emotion in travel right now is not convenience.\n\nIt''s trust.\n\n## The next chapter\n\nThe winning travel companies of the next decade will not be the ones with the largest inventory.\n\nThey will be the ones that restore the relationship between a traveler and a human who knows where to send them.\n\nAI helps. It draws the map, narrows the field, drafts the framework. But the soul of a great trip is still selected by someone with judgment — a creator who lives in Mexico City, an advisor who has booked the Maldives forty times, a hotelier who knows which suite catches the light.\n\nThe marketplace I want to use is the one where those people are findable, accountable, and on the same platform as the trip itself.\n\nThat is the marketplace we are building.\n\n> The future of travel is more personal, more curated, and more human.\n\nWe are early.\n\nBut for the first time in a long time, the most exciting thing happening in travel is not another booking engine.\n\nIt''s the return of perspective.'
WHERE slug = 'state-of-the-modern-travel-marketplace';

-- Article 2: Why We Built Goldsainte
UPDATE public.newsroom_articles
SET
  author_id = 'd4ec9c8f-0b9f-4e6e-ad2f-f8c701df028e',
  subtitle = 'A founder''s note on luxury transportation, 350 cities, and the moment I realized travelers needed more than a car.',
  excerpt = 'A personal note from the founder on why Goldsainte evolved from luxury transportation in 50+ countries into a global travel marketplace built around trust.',
  hero_image_url = 'https://iwdevxltjuedijrcdejs.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/newsroom-media/articles/hero-founder-note.jpg',
  hero_image_alt = 'Andre C. Powell, Jr. seated at a marble counter in a quiet luxury hotel lobby with a leather notebook and espresso.',
  hero_image_credit = 'Photograph for Goldsainte',
  og_image_url = 'https://iwdevxltjuedijrcdejs.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/newsroom-media/articles/hero-founder-note.jpg',
  tags = ARRAY['Founder Note','Goldsainte Origin','Luxury Travel','Marketplaces'],
  body = E'The first car I dispatched was in Charlotte. The most recent one was in Dubai.\n\nIn between, Goldsainte''s luxury transportation platform quietly expanded into more than 350 cities across over 50 countries — almost always behind the curtain of someone else''s trip.\n\nWe were the polished detail. The black car waiting in the rain. The driver who knew not to talk on the way to the meeting.\n\nIt was a good business.\n\nIt also taught me something I didn''t expect.\n\n> The car was rarely the problem. The trip around it was.\n\n## What I kept hearing in the back seat\n\nIn every city, in dozens of accents, the same conversation kept happening between client and concierge in the back seat:\n\n*"The hotel wasn''t what the photos showed."*\n\n*"The restaurant we booked closed two weeks ago — no one updated the site."*\n\n*"My travel agent retired and I haven''t found anyone like her."*\n\n*"I planned this entire trip myself and I''m exhausted."*\n\nThese are not complaints about price. They are complaints about trust.\n\nThe people in those back seats had means. They had taste. They had access. What they did not have was a system that respected their time and their standards from the moment of inspiration to the moment of return.\n\n![A worn leather travel journal, vintage passport, brass compass, and a single black coffee under warm lamplight beside a rain-streaked city window.](https://iwdevxltjuedijrcdejs.supabase.co/storage/v1/object/public/newsroom-media/articles/inline-founder-desk.jpg)\n\n## The shift\n\nI realized I had built a company that solved one thirty-minute window of a seven-day trip.\n\nThat is when the idea for Goldsainte AI began to take shape.\n\nNot as a "platform play." Not as an AI bet. As a quiet observation:\n\n> Modern travelers do not want another booking engine. They want trusted expertise, inspired discovery, and a better way to design the journey.\n\nThe transportation business taught me how high the bar is for premium service. The travel business showed me how rarely that bar is met across the full arc of a trip.\n\nGoldsainte AI is the answer to that gap.\n\n## What we are building\n\nA single platform where travelers can:\n\n- Be inspired by creators who actually go to the places they post about.\n- Be guided by independent advisors who book the same suite three times a year and know which one catches the morning light.\n- Be paired with hospitality partners who have something to lose by disappointing you.\n- Be supported by AI that drafts, narrows, and structures — and then steps aside for a human who has standards.\n\nIt is a marketplace, yes. But the operating principle is not scale.\n\nIt is taste, executed at scale.\n\n## A personal word\n\nI grew up watching my family treat hospitality as a discipline. Plates set properly. Doors held. Names remembered.\n\nThat is the standard the back seat taught me to protect.\n\nGoldsainte AI is, at its core, an attempt to bring that standard to the entire journey — not just the thirty minutes between the airport and the hotel.\n\nIf we do it well, modern travelers will stop tab-hopping at midnight.\n\nThey''ll text a person they trust.\n\nThey''ll get something extraordinary back.\n\nThat is the company I want to build.\n\nAnd that is why we are here.\n\n— Andre C. Powell, Jr.  \n*Founder & CEO, Goldsainte*'
WHERE slug = 'why-we-built-goldsainte';

